@NODE "16Col" "The 16 Colour Palette"

  @{B}16 Colours on your Workbench@{UB}

  The 16 colours that I use on my Workbench are those from RomIcons9.

  This is a direct quote from RomIcons9 RI.Guide about the installation of a modified 16 colour 
  Workbench.

  Take it away Roman.

 "Steps to install my 16 colour palette on your system:

  1. Change your screenmode to 16 colors.
  2. Load the User-Startup into your editor and change the MagicWB-Daemon to:
     Run >NIL: C:MagicWB-Demon 4,123,123,123 5,175,175,175 6,170,144,124 7,255,169,151 8,0,0,255 9,50,50,50 10,96,128,96 11,226,209,119 12,255,212,203 13,122,96,72 14,210,210,210 15,229,93,93
  3. Do the same with your Startup-Sequence
  4. Load Prefs/Palette and change the last four colours to
            255,212,203   122,96,72   210,210,210   229,93,93
     and save it. After re-boot everything should work fine."

  There you have it all the instructions you need to make your MWB2.0 look really @{" Cool " SYSTEM "TIGuide/SOUND TIGuide/Cool1.snd q"} too!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "why" "Not Another Set Of Icons |-O"

  @{B}Does The World Need Another Set Of Icons?@{UB}

  This is the question my wife asks me all the time while I sit infront of my A1200 on Sunday
  afternoons drawing icons and listening to The Future Sound Of London or T.I.S.M.

  The answer, is of course, Yes! More icons mean more choice and that can't be a bad thing :-). 
  Most of these icons in this package were drawn for other people who requested icons for packages
  and programs that they use (They must think I can draw or something ;->). They may be of no
  use to anyone but them but you can chop them up and use them for other things with my 
  compliments. All I ask is that you give me the same credit that I give those from whom I have 
  borrowed images and ideas. It's a better term than copied don't you think?
@ENDNODE

@NODE "point" "Colour & Pointer"

  @{b}Colour & Pointer@{ub}

  As I have discussed the 16 MWB palette elsewhere @{" Click Here " LINK "16Col"} to find out more.
 

  This @{" pointer " SYSTEM "Multiview TIGuide/Pointer"} is my creation. 


  After seeing the multitude of arrows and other weird and wonderful pointers out there I 
  thought it was time to develop my own pointer. It is a picture of a cartoon-like hand 
  with an out-stretched index finger for the pointer. The wait picture is like the original
  Zzz cloud. I think they look much better than arrows and give my @{" AMIGA " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/Yeah.snd q"} (and maybe yours too) 
  an individual touch that only owners of @{" INTEL Based Machines " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/DoesNot.snd q"} can only drool over - Ha Ha.


  @{" Geert Coelmont " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/Yeah.snd q"} from Belgium found my pointer so interesting that he made a little programme
  to animate it. When you click the left mouse button the index finger of my hand pointer bends
  in response. So when you click an icon the hand actually pushes the icon down. It's a cute hack
  that has been stable on my computer for nearly six months without so much as a hick-up! Try it
  I know you'll like it. I know I do!

  To get PointerClick to work on your system just follow these simple steps.

  @{B}1)@{UB} Copy the supplied Pointer.Prefs to "ENVARC:sys/". This will replace
   your current mousepointer (make a copy if you don't want to loose it).
  @{B}2)@{UB} Copy PointerClick to "C:"
  @{B}3)@{UB} Add this line to your S:User-Startup:

		@{fg shine}run >nil: <nil: C:PointerClick@{fg text}

  @{B}4)@{UB} Reboot your machine
  @{B}5)@{UB} Push left mousebutton !!

  @{B}Note@{UB}: Nothing happens if the original 'hand' pointer is not active.
        Don't start PointerClick more than once.
        PointerClick cannot be deactivated, except by resetting.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "icons" "TomIcons4 Information"

  @{b}16 Colour Icons@{ub}

  Hi Everyone :-)!

  Here is my forth collection of MWB Icons and other stuff that I have drawn or created over the 
  last few months. Most of them require the modified 16 colour palette discussed in @{" RomIcons9 " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/wahoo.snd q"}.
  @{" Click Here " LINK "16Col"} for further details.

  I am not an artist but use a registered version of Iconian and Picticon to cut and paste 
  images to produce the icons that are on your screen now. Once in a while Personal Paint 6.3 
  came in handy as well ;-).

  Why do I insist to draw my icons using a 16 colour pallete? I find that if I use the dark grey
  colour (Colour 9:50, 50, 50) instead of the original blue (Colour 4:59, 103, 162) a better 
  contrast and 3D effect is achieved. If you are using an 8 colour WB just recolour any icons,
  that you may find useful, to your own pallete. 

  Many of the icons in this package are those from other packages which I have recoloured and 
  remodelled to accentuate their 3D features. Some, however, are completely original and may not
  look as professional as those which I have "borrowed" and played around with ;-).

  @{" Click Here " SYSTEM "Multiview SCREEN TomsWB.iff"} for a brief look at my Workbench Screen.

  I have also included some icons for two commercial programmes:- Scala and Organiser. I own both 
  these programmes and was not satisfied with the boring 4 colour efforts provided by the
  programmers, so I made my own. The Scala icons use colour 8 (0, 0, 255) as a background which
  may or may not be compatible with your workbench. I used this colour because I run MagicCopper
  which gives that great looking gradient background seen in my WB pic.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "boot" "Boot-Pic"

  @{B}Boot Picture@{UB}

  Here is a picture which is suitable as boot-pic using a programme such as BootScreen or
  something similar. It is in the PAL HiRes Interlace format.

  This picture of a @{" Tree-frog " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/Frog q"} was converted from its JPEG original using Persoanl Paint 6.3®. 
  I think it's more interesting to display a picture which is aesthetically pleasing and shows off 
  the colour capibilities of the Amiga rather than something that tells the owner which operating 
  system he/she is using (they should know this anyway, it's their computer!).

  @{" Kermit " SYSTEM "MultiView SCREEN BootPic/TreeFrog.iff"} - the green amphibian.
@ENDNODE

